import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

# INTENT: mkt-context commentary for Genesis 36–37. Ch36 = Esau/Edom genealogy
#   closing off the non-covenant line before the Joseph narrative begins.
#   Ch37 = Joseph narrative opens; audience would recognize dream conventions,
#   ANE slave trade prices, and the irony of Ishmaelite kinship.
# CHANGE? If data/commentary/mkt-context/genesis.json schema changes, update
#   load_comm/save_comm helpers in Z_COMMENTARY_SCRIPT_GUIDE.md accordingly.
# VERIFY: After running, python3 -c "import json; d=json.load(open('data/commentary/mkt-context/genesis.json')); print(len(d.get('36',{})), len(d.get('37',{})))" should print "43 36".

NEW_DATA = {
"36": {
"1": "<p>The formula <em>toledot</em> (&#8220;account of the family line&#8221;) appears twice for Esau&#8212;here (36:1) and again at 36:9&#8212;marking a double closure. In ANE genealogical convention, listing a non-heir&#8217;s descendants at length signals the end of that branch&#8217;s narrative significance. The parenthetical &#8220;that is, Edom&#8221; fuses the man and the nation; the audience hears the toledot as the story of a people, not just a patriarch.</p>",
"2": "<p>The chapter opens by naming three wives, but their lineage creates apparent tension with earlier texts (Gen 26:34; 28:9 list different names). ANE genealogies regularly harmonize or compress family trees across generations; what looks like contradiction is often telescoping&#8212;a granddaughter called daughter, a clan name used for an individual. The audience would not expect chronological precision; genealogies established territory and alliance, not biography.</p>",
"3": "<p>Basemath daughter of Ishmael is introduced separately, signaling that Esau deliberately sought a non-Canaanite wife after his parents&#8217; displeasure (28:8&#8211;9). Taking an Ishmaelite wife aligned Esau with the other &#8220;outside&#8221; son of Abraham; both lines are legitimate descendants yet outside the Abrahamic covenant promise that runs through Isaac&#8212;Jacob.</p>",
"4": "<p>Eliphaz (&#8220;my God is fine gold&#8221; or &#8220;God is strength&#8221;) will become the most prominent name among these descendants; his son Teman gives Edom its proverbial wisdom reputation (Jer 49:7; Obad 8). The audience familiar with the book of Job would recognize Eliphaz the Temanite as Esau&#8217;s grandson&#8212;a detail the genealogy quietly plants.</p>",
"5": "<p>The summary &#8220;born to him in Canaan&#8221; prepares for the movement that follows in vv6&#8211;8. Esau&#8217;s sons are Canaanite-born but will not remain there; their inheritance lies in Seir, not in the promised land. The land of Canaan was promised to Jacob&#8217;s line (28:13); Esau&#8217;s line must find its portion elsewhere&#8212;which it does, by divine arrangement not recorded here but assumed.</p>",
"6": "<p>Esau&#8217;s departure echoes Abram and Lot&#8217;s separation (ch 13:5&#8211;12): too many animals, too little land, mutual agreement to part. In both scenes the subordinate figure moves first to make space for the covenant heir. ANE audience would read this as honorable withdrawal rather than expulsion; Esau takes his wealth and goes &#8220;to a land some distance,&#8221; preserving dignity on both sides.</p>",
"7": "<p>&#8220;The land where they were staying could not support them both because of their livestock&#8221;&#8212;identical logic to ch 13:6 (Abram/Lot). The narrative thus frames Esau&#8217;s exodus as structurally parallel to Lot&#8217;s: both are separated from the covenant line by mutual economic necessity, both go east or south-east. The separation is providential, not hostile.</p>",
"8": "<p>Seir is the central massif running south of the Dead Sea, today&#8217;s Jordanian highlands around Petra. The Horites (&#8220;cave-dwellers&#8221; or a specific ethnic group; see vv20&#8211;30) originally inhabited it; Esau&#8217;s descendants absorbed or displaced them (Deut 2:12, 22). The repeated identification &#8220;Esau (that is, Edom)&#8221; signals that the audience should read every Edomite reference in subsequent biblical history through this ancestral lens.</p>",
"9": "<p>A second <em>toledot</em> opens at v9, now specifying &#8220;the father of the Edomites in the hill country of Seir.&#8221; Two toledot openings for one person is unusual; scholars suggest the first (v1) introduces the man and his Canaanite-born family, while the second (v9) opens the Seirite lineage after the move. The structure mirrors the dual blessing/departure narrative of chs 27&#8211;28 and 32&#8211;33.</p>",
"10": "<p>Eliphaz and Reuel are the founding sons of the two main Edomite tribal confederacies. Their names and their sons&#8217; names (Teman, Omar, Zepho, Gatam, Kenaz for Eliphaz; Nahath, Zerah, Shammah, Mizzah for Reuel) map onto tribal territories in Edom. Ancient Near Eastern genealogical lists often represent political structures&#8212;&#8220;son of X&#8221; means &#8220;subordinate to the clan of X&#8221;&#8212;rather than strict biological filiation.</p>",
"11": "<p>Teman becomes a place-name in Edom synonymous with wisdom (Jer 49:7; Hab 3:3; Obad 9). The prophet Amos condemns Teman (Am 1:11&#8211;12). Kenaz is ancestral to the Kenizzites (Num 32:12; Josh 14:6), a clan that is later absorbed into Judah&#8212;suggesting that some Edomite sub-groups eventually merged into Israel&#8217;s tribal structure.</p>",
"12": "<p>Timna as Eliphaz&#8217;s concubine rather than wife reflects ANE household law: concubine-sons inherit less and occupy subordinate positions. Amalek&#8212;son of a concubine, not a wife&#8212;becomes Israel&#8217;s archetypal enemy (Exod 17:8&#8211;16; Deut 25:17&#8211;19). His placement here as a secondary descendant of Esau establishes him as outside both covenant and full tribal legitimacy from the outset.</p>",
"13": "<p>The sons of Reuel occupy the southern Edomite territories around Bozrah and the Negev borderlands. Zerah is a common Semitic name (&#8220;rising&#8221; or &#8220;brightness&#8221;); Shammah and Mizzah appear to be tribal eponyms. These names recur in prophetic oracles against Edom (Isa 34; Jer 49; Ezek 25; Obad), showing the genealogy is not merely antiquarian&#8212;it provided the historical backdrop for later geopolitics.</p>",
"14": "<p>Oholibamah is both a personal name and later a chief-name (v41), suggesting she may be a clan ancestress whose descendants are named after her. In ANE genealogy, eponymous ancestresses are rarer than eponymous ancestors but not unknown; they signal matrilineal significance within a patrilineal system&#8212;possibly because the clan traced rights through her Hivite/Horite lineage in Seir.</p>",
"15": "<p>The term <em>allûp</em> (chief/clan leader) occurs twelve times in this chapter (vv15&#8211;19, 29&#8211;30, 40&#8211;43), marking Edom as a confederation of tribal chieftaincies rather than a centralized monarchy at this stage. The same term is used in Exod 15:15 (&#8220;the chiefs of Edom will be terrified&#8221;), indicating this political structure persisted into the Exodus period.</p>",
"16": "<p>Chief Korah among Eliphaz&#8217;s line should not be confused with the Korah of the Levite rebellion in Numbers 16; the name was common. Amalek appearing in the chief-list as well as in the genealogy signals that Amalek&#8217;s clan achieved full chieftaincy status despite concubine origins&#8212;political power overriding legal subordination over time.</p>",
"17": "<p>The chiefs of Reuel (Nahath, Zerah, Shammah, Mizzah) occupy territories south and east of the Dead Sea. Bozrah (associated with Jobab in v33) was the ancient capital of Edom, modern Buseirah in Jordan, and archaeological excavations there reveal Iron Age occupation; the ANE audience would know it as Edom&#8217;s preeminent city.</p>",
"18": "<p>Oholibamah&#8217;s sons&#8212;Jeush, Jalam, Korah&#8212;represent the Horite-Hivite lineage within Edom, the indigenous element absorbed into Esau&#8217;s confederation. The inclusion of these three lines (Adah&#8217;s, Basemath&#8217;s, Oholibamah&#8217;s sons) reflects how Edom&#8217;s polity combined multiple ethnic streams: Semitic through Esau, indigenous through Horite wives, Ishmaelite through Basemath.</p>",
"19": "<p>The summary verse closes the genealogical register and transitions to the Horite lineage. By first listing Esau&#8217;s sons as chiefs, then listing the Horites as the prior inhabitants, the text acknowledges that Edom&#8217;s territory was not empty: it was conquered or absorbed from the Horites, paralleling Israel&#8217;s later displacement of Canaanites (Deut 2:12 makes this parallel explicit).</p>",
"20": "<p>The Horites (Heb. <em>ḥōrî</em>) appear in the Table of Nations (Gen 10:6 as &#8220;Hivites&#8221; in some manuscripts). Their name may derive from <em>ḥôr</em> (&#8220;cave&#8221;) or from Hurrian, the Indo-European people who dominated much of the Fertile Crescent in the Middle Bronze Age. Seir&#8217;s terrain&#8212;rocky ravines and sandstone cliffs&#8212;fits both etymologies. The Hurrian connection would explain Nuzi parallels seen in the Genesis narratives (teraphim as inheritance tokens, bride-price customs).</p>",
"21": "<p>Seven Horite chiefs are listed (Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon, Anah, Dishon, Ezer, Dishan), mirroring the structure of Esau&#8217;s seven sons by three wives. The parallelism is deliberate: two sets of seven chiefs in the same land, one set being absorbed by the other. The Horite chiefs are identified as occupying Edom&#8212;meaning Edom (Esau&#8217;s territory) and Seir (Horite territory) have already merged by the time the list was composed.</p>",
"22": "<p>Timna as Lotan&#8217;s sister links the Horite and Edomite genealogies: Timna (Horite) becomes concubine to Eliphaz (Edomite, v12), bearing Amalek. This cross-genealogy figure explains why Timna appears in both lists. It also shows intermarriage cementing the Horite-Edomite fusion; the genealogy records the ethnic blending that produced historic Edom.</p>",
"23": "<p>Shobal&#8217;s sons include Manahath, a name shared with a Benjaminite clan in 1 Chron 8:6&#8212;another example of Edomite/Israelite name overlap suggesting later population movement or shared terminology. ANE personal names were drawn from a common Semitic stock; identical names across lineages do not necessarily imply the same individuals.</p>",
"24": "<p>The parenthetical about Anah discovering &#8220;hot springs in the desert&#8221; (Heb. <em>hayyĕmim</em>, uncertain; LXX reads &#8220;the Emim&#8221; i.e. a people-group; Vulgate reads &#8220;warm water&#8221;) is the kind of antiquarian notice that ANE genealogies occasionally include to explain place-names or clan reputations. The note locates Anah as a notable figure in the Transjordanian oral tradition even before Esau&#8217;s line arrived.</p>",
"25": "<p>Oholibamah daughter of Anah appears both as Esau&#8217;s wife (v2) and here as Anah&#8217;s child, confirming the genealogical bridge: Esau married into the Horite chieftaincy through Oholibamah, giving his sons Horite blood and Horite territorial claims. This was a classic ANE strategy&#8212;marrying a daughter of a local chief to legitimize territorial occupation.</p>",
"26": "<p>Dishon&#8217;s sons are four names unattested elsewhere; they likely represent small sub-clans within the Horite confederation that lost independent identity as Edomite absorption proceeded. The careful listing preserves memory of these absorbed groups&#8212;a common ANE genealogical function: legitimizing the present order by tracing all its components back to recognized ancestors.</p>",
"27": "<p>Ezer (&#8220;help&#8221;) as a Horite chief name appears in later Israelite genealogies (1 Chron 4:4; 7:21; 12:9), again illustrating the shared Semitic name pool and perhaps post-conquest intermingling of populations across the Transjordan and Negev regions.</p>",
"28": "<p>Uz son of Dishan is potentially the eponym of &#8220;the land of Uz&#8221; where Job lived (Job 1:1; Lam 4:21 places Uz in Edom). If so, the genealogy quietly locates Job&#8217;s homeland within the Horite-Edomite region&#8212;explaining why Job&#8217;s friend Eliphaz comes from Teman (also in Edom, v11) and why the book of Job has affinities with Edomite wisdom tradition.</p>",
"29": "<p>The seven Horite chiefs are listed a second time (vv29&#8211;30) after their genealogy (vv20&#8211;28), mirroring the double-listing of Esau&#8217;s chiefs (genealogy vv10&#8211;19, chief-list vv40&#8211;43). The repetition is a standard ANE literary technique: present the lineage, then formally enumerate the resulting political offices. It signals that the genealogy has legal and territorial, not merely historical, significance.</p>",
"30": "<p>&#8220;According to their divisions, in the land of Seir&#8221;&#8212;the Horites are formally characterized as organized by divisions (<em>mĕḥittōt</em>, also translated &#8220;clans&#8221; or &#8220;divisions&#8221;), a term used later for Israel&#8217;s tribal units. The parallel language suggests the text presents Horite Seir as a structured polity, not a haphazard population, legitimizing Edom&#8217;s later claim to the same territory as an ordered succession of governance.</p>",
"31": "<p>&#8220;Before any Israelite king reigned&#8221;&#8212;this notice has generated significant discussion. It implies awareness that Israel would eventually have kings (anticipating Samuel&#8211;Kings), consistent with Balaam&#8217;s oracle (Num 24:17&#8211;19) and Jacob&#8217;s blessing of Judah (49:10). ANE king-lists with formulaic &#8220;X reigned, then died, Y succeeded&#8221; patterns are well-attested (Sumerian King List, Egyptian king lists); this passage imitates that genre. The Edomite king-list predates Israel&#8217;s monarchy by centuries, establishing Edom as the more &#8220;advanced&#8221; polity in the ancestral period.</p>",
"32": "<p>Bela son of Beor&#8212;the name Beor is identical to Balaam&#8217;s father&#8217;s name (Num 22:5), though the individuals are distinct. Dinhabah is unidentified archaeologically. The non-dynastic succession pattern (each king from a different city, different father) is characteristic of early confederate kingship in which the strongest chief is recognized rather than hereditary succession operating. Edom maintained this non-dynastic pattern through all eight kings listed.</p>",
"33": "<p>Jobab son of Zerah from Bozrah: Bozrah (modern Buseirah, Jordan) was Edom&#8217;s most important city, featuring in prophetic judgment oracles (Isa 34:6; 63:1; Jer 49:13; Amos 1:12). Excavations at Buseirah confirm occupation from the 8th&#8211;7th centuries BCE as an administrative center. The appearance of Bozrah early in Edom&#8217;s king-list indicates its prestige predated the Iron Age occupation archaeologists have dated.</p>",
"34": "<p>Husham from the Temanites: Teman (named after Esau&#8217;s grandson, v11) is consistently associated with wisdom in the prophets (Jer 49:7; Obad 8&#8211;9). A Temanite king suggests that clan was politically dominant at this stage. The Temanites&#8217; intellectual reputation in the ancient world makes Eliphaz the Temanite (Job 2:11) a figure of recognized authority&#8212;his origins in a respected Edomite wisdom tradition lend him credibility that the book of Job ultimately undercuts.</p>",
"35": "<p>Hadad son of Bedad &#8220;who defeated Midian in the country of Moab&#8221;&#8212;this is the only king whose martial achievement is noted. The Edom-Midian conflict in Moab suggests competition over the King&#8217;s Highway trade route east of the Dead Sea. Midian (from Abraham&#8217;s line through Keturah, 25:2) and Edom (through Esau) are both Abrahamic outside-covenant lines competing for Transjordanian dominance.</p>",
"36": "<p>Samlah from Masrekah: Masrekah is unidentified but the name suggests a place of vines (<em>śōrēq</em> = choice vine). The non-succession from Hadad (different family, different city) confirms the elective rather than dynastic nature of Edomite kingship at this period&#8212;each king was chosen from the most powerful available chief rather than from the prior king&#8217;s heirs.</p>",
"37": "<p>Shaul from Rehoboth &#8220;on the river&#8221;&#8212;the river is likely the Euphrates (as in Gen 31:21; 1 Kgs 4:21), which would place Rehoboth far to the north and suggest this king came from a distant branch of Edomite or related Semitic stock. Alternatively, the phrase may denote a wadi. The geographic spread of these kings&#8217; origins (Teman, Bozrah, Moab, Euphrates) shows Edom&#8217;s confederation drew leadership from a wide territorial base.</p>",
"38": "<p>Baal-Hanan son of Akbor: the name Baal-Hanan (&#8220;Baal is gracious&#8221;) reflects Baal-worship that was embedded even in Edomite royal nomenclature. This is not remarkable for the Bronze Age&#8212;Baal was a generic storm-deity title across Canaan and Syria. The presence of Baal-names in Edom&#8217;s king-list shows the same Canaanite religious milieu that permeated all the surrounding peoples including, periodically, Israel.</p>",
"39": "<p>The eighth king Hadad (same name as the fifth; not the same individual) is the last listed. His wife Mehetabel daughter of Matred, daughter of Me-Zahab is unusual: wives of kings are rarely named in ANE king-lists. The matrilineal detail may signal that Hadad&#8217;s legitimacy derived partly from his marriage into a prestigious Edomite noble family&#8212;the naming of her grandmother suggesting deep genealogical roots. Me-Zahab means &#8220;waters of gold,&#8221; possibly a place-name turned ancestral name.</p>",
"40": "<p>A second chief-list (vv40&#8211;43) parallels and differs from the earlier one (vv15&#8211;19): different names, described as territorial chiefs &#8220;according to their clans and regions&#8221; rather than descended from specific sons. This list likely represents Edom&#8217;s political organization at a later period&#8212;post-absorption of Horites, post-monarchy&#8212;when the confederation reorganized around regional districts rather than purely genealogical lines.</p>",
"41": "<p>Oholibamah as a chief-name (not the wife of Esau) shows the phenomenon of female eponyms giving their names to territorial units. In ANE administrative practice, a district could bear the name of a prestigious ancestress just as it could bear a male eponym; the territory of Oholibamah likely corresponded to the Horite-Edomite borderland where Esau&#8217;s Hivite wife&#8217;s people were concentrated.</p>",
"42": "<p>Kenaz as a chief-name (also Eliphaz&#8217;s son in v15) reappears here as a territorial designation. The Kenizzites, affiliated with this name, appear in the Abrahamic land grant (Gen 15:19) as one of ten peoples whose land was promised to Abraham&#8217;s descendants&#8212;meaning Kenizzite territory in the Negev/Edom border region was part of the original promised land boundary.</p>",
"43": "<p>The closing formula &#8220;This was Esau the father of the Edomites&#8221; mirrors the formula used throughout Genesis to close a toledot section. Having spent 43 verses on Esau&#8217;s descendants&#8212;more than any other non-covenant figure in Genesis&#8212;the text now formally closes that branch and turns to Jacob&#8217;s line (37:1). The audience understands: Edom is real, organized, and significant, but the covenant story resumes with Jacob. The juxtaposition of Esau&#8217;s already-established kingdom with Jacob&#8217;s still-wandering family underscores that divine election does not track worldly success.</p>"
},
"37": {
"2": "<p>The <em>toledot</em> of Jacob opens with Joseph, signaling that Jacob&#8217;s story is now carried through his most prominent son. Joseph is seventeen, old enough to work but young enough to be under fraternal authority. His role tending flocks with the sons of the concubine-wives (Bilhah/Zilpah) places him alongside the lower-status brothers&#8212;yet his report to Jacob suggests he already occupies a supervisory or informant role, a social dynamic charged with resentment potential in any honor-shame culture.</p>",
"3": "<p>The <em>kĕtōnet passîm</em> (&#8220;ornate robe&#8221;) is one of the most debated garments in the Hebrew Bible. <em>Passim</em> may mean &#8220;palms and soles&#8221; (a full-length garment covering extremities, marking non-manual labor), &#8220;many colors&#8221; (LXX: <em>chitōna poikilon</em>), or simply &#8220;decorated.&#8221; The same phrase appears only in 2 Sam 13:18&#8211;19 where Tamar, a royal princess, wears it&#8212;confirming it marks elite, set-apart status. Jacob&#8217;s gift signals his intent to elevate Joseph over his brothers, a dangerous public statement of preference in a polygynous household governed by birth-order expectations.</p>",
"4": "<p>&#8220;Could not say a kind word to him&#8221; (Heb. <em>lōʾ yāḵĕlû dabbĕrô lĕšālōm</em>) is literally &#8220;could not speak to him in peace/wholeness.&#8221; <em>Šālôm</em> in ANE usage is the normal greeting formula; its absence signals complete social breakdown. The brothers&#8217; hatred is not merely emotional&#8212;it represents a severing of the covenant-family social bond. Honor-shame dynamics: Jacob&#8217;s public favor for Joseph was a public shaming of the other sons, especially the firstborn Reuben and the sons of Leah who expected precedence.</p>",
"5": "<p>Dreams in the ancient Near East were universally recognized as potential divine communications. Egyptian dream interpretation was a developed science (attested in the Chester Beatty Dream Book, c. 1350 BCE); Mesopotamian omen literature included dream omens extensively. An Israelite audience would hear Joseph&#8217;s dreams not as subjective visions but as divine disclosures&#8212;the question was always <em>interpretation</em>, not whether they were meaningful. Joseph&#8217;s naïve recounting shows either social obtuseness or courage.</p>",
"6": "<p>Joseph&#8217;s preamble &#8220;Listen to this dream I had&#8221; uses an imperative that in Hebrew carries a note of urgency or demand (<em>šimʿû-nāʾ</em>). In a culture where elders and firstborns commanded deference, a seventeen-year-old younger brother demanding that his elders listen was itself provocative. The narrative presents Joseph as socially unaware of the dynamics he is inflaming&#8212;or perhaps testing his brothers&#8217; willingness to hear.</p>",
"7": "<p>The sheaf-dream is agricultural and egalitarian in imagery&#8212;all brothers binding grain together&#8212;until Joseph&#8217;s sheaf rises and the others bow. Sheaf-bowing in Egyptian harvest ritual art symbolizes tribute and subordination. The dream&#8217;s imagery would be legible to any agricultural society: the one whose sheaf stands upright commands the others&#8217; produce. First-century readers of Genesis in Egypt&#8212;the LXX audience&#8212;would have found the Egyptian context especially resonant given where Joseph is headed.</p>",
"8": "<p>The brothers&#8217; interpretation is immediate and correct: &#8220;Do you intend to reign over us?&#8221; In ANE dream interpretation, sheaves representing people or nations bowing is straightforward political symbolism (cf. Pharaoh&#8217;s dreams in ch 40&#8211;41). The brothers are not slow or foolish&#8212;they understand exactly what the dream claims and reject it. Their hatred intensifies because the dream asserts a social reversal that violates every birth-order and maternal-status norm they inhabit.</p>",
"9": "<p>The second dream escalates from agricultural (earthly) to cosmic imagery: sun, moon, and eleven stars. In ANE cosmology, celestial bodies were divine or semi-divine powers; the sun was often the royal deity (Egyptian Ra, Mesopotamian Shamash). Eleven stars bowing to a twelfth inverts cosmic order. The scope of this dream is imperial&#8212;not just family but cosmic sovereignty. Joseph telling this dream to both father and brothers suggests he lacks either discretion or the capacity to suppress what he believes is divine revelation.</p>",
"10": "<p>Jacob&#8217;s rebuke is significant: even the favored father checks himself. &#8220;Will your mother and I&#8230; come and bow down?&#8221;&#8212;Jacob interprets the sun and moon as himself and Rachel (or Leah, since Rachel was already dead, 35:19, a tension commentators note). The rebuke is public and calibrates the family&#8217;s response. Yet v11 adds that &#8220;his father kept the matter in mind&#8221;&#8212;a phrase used of Mary in Luke 2:51, signaling that the rebuke is performative while the content is taken seriously.</p>",
"11": "<p>&#8220;His brothers were jealous of him, but his father kept the matter in mind.&#8221; The contrast between fraternal jealousy and paternal contemplation structures the tension. <em>Qanāʾ</em> (jealous/zealous) is a strong term used of God&#8217;s own jealousy (Exod 20:5); here it marks the brothers&#8217; resentment as existentially threatening, not merely petty. The father&#8217;s silent pondering mirrors the response of those who receive and weigh prophetic words rather than immediately acting on or dismissing them.</p>",
"12": "<p>Shechem appears again as the brothers&#8217; grazing location&#8212;the same city where Dinah was violated (ch 34) and where the brothers massacred the male population. That the brothers return to Shechem after that event, evidently without consequence, suggests either time has passed and the incident is forgotten by local memory, or that the highlands of Shechem were so pastorally valuable that the family had no alternative grazing grounds. Their presence there also removes them from Jacob&#8217;s immediate oversight.</p>",
"13": "<p>Jacob sends Joseph alone from the Valley of Hebron (Mamre region) to Shechem&#8212;a journey of approximately 80 km (50 miles) through highland terrain. The distance is significant: once Joseph leaves, no one can intercede quickly. Jacob&#8217;s willingness to send his favored son alone on this errand has struck readers as odd&#8212;some see it as narrative naivety, others as providential necessity. The Valley of Hebron is below sea level relative to the highlands; the &#8220;valley&#8221; is geographically incongruous since Hebron sits on high ground, suggesting the phrase may be idiomatic or symbolic.</p>",
"14": "<p>&#8220;See how your brothers and the flocks are getting on&#8221; (lit. &#8220;see the welfare/<em>šālôm</em> of your brothers&#8221;) is ironic: Joseph is sent to inquire about <em>šālôm</em> from brothers who cannot speak <em>šālôm</em> to him (v4). The mission recapitulates the narrative tension in a single phrase. Joseph sets out &#8220;very well&#8221; (Heb. <em>hinneni</em>, &#8220;here I am&#8221;&#8212;the same response Abraham gave when called to sacrifice Isaac, 22:1, 11): a word of ready obedience that in both cases leads toward death.</p>",
"15": "<p>The unnamed man who finds Joseph wandering in the fields at Shechem functions as a providential guide in the narrative&#8212;a type of divine messenger directing events. ANE audiences would recognize the &#8220;mysterious helper&#8221; motif from folklore and epic (cf. the divine helpers in Gilgamesh). Without this man, Joseph never reaches Dothan; without reaching Dothan, the brothers&#8217; plot never converges with him. The man&#8217;s anonymity signals narrative function over character development.</p>",
"16": "<p>&#8220;I&#8217;m looking for my brothers&#8221;&#8212;the Hebrew is simple and direct. Joseph&#8217;s openness to a stranger reflects either trust or the social norm that travelers freely answered such questions; to refuse would be suspicious and inhospitable. The question about grazing location is practical&#8212;flocks move&#8212;and the man&#8217;s knowledge of the brothers&#8217; plan to go to Dothan is presented without explanation, another feature of the providential-helper motif.</p>",
"17": "<p>Dothan (Heb. <em>Dōṯān</em>) is identified with Tell Dothan in the Samaria hills, approximately 20 km north of Shechem. Archaeological excavations (1953&#8211;1960, J. P. Free) confirmed continuous occupation from the Early Bronze Age through the Roman period. The Dothan Valley is fertile and well-watered, excellent grazing territory. The city appears again in 2 Kgs 6:13 when Elisha is surrounded by Aramean forces there&#8212;the same isolation from help that the valley provides in Joseph&#8217;s story.</p>",
"18": "<p>&#8220;They plotted to kill him&#8221; (Heb. <em>wayyitnaqqĕlû ʿālāyw lĕhāmîtô</em>)&#8212;the verb <em>nāqal</em> (Hithpael) means &#8220;to deal craftily/cunningly.&#8221; The brothers&#8217; conspiracy is calculated, not impulsive; they have seen him from a distance and take time to plan. The distance detail (&#8220;before he reached them&#8221;) gives them the leisure of deliberation, making their planned violence premeditated rather than reactive&#8212;a legal distinction ANE law recognized.</p>",
"19": "<p>&#8220;Here comes that dreamer!&#8221; (Heb. <em>baʿal haḥălōmôt hallāzeh</em>&#8212;lit. &#8220;this master of dreams&#8221;). <em>Baʿal</em> + noun is a common Hebrew idiom for someone characterized by a quality (e.g. &#8220;master of anger&#8221; = hothead). The brothers&#8217; derisive label identifies Joseph entirely by his dreams&#8212;the very thing that most threatens them. Their plan targets not just Joseph but the dreams: &#8220;then we&#8217;ll see what comes of his dreams&#8221; (v20). The narrative shows them trying to falsify a divine oracle by eliminating the oracle&#8217;s subject.</p>",
"20": "<p>The plan: kill, throw in a cistern (<em>bôr</em>), blame a wild animal. Cisterns (<em>bōrôt</em>) were common in the Levantine highlands&#8212;bell-shaped rock-cut chambers storing rainwater. An empty cistern in summer was a convenient disposal pit; its depth (often 3&#8211;5 meters) made unaided escape impossible. The brothers&#8217; cover story&#8212;a wild animal (<em>ḥayyāh rāʿāh</em>)&#8212;is plausible in the pastoral landscape where lions and bears still operated (cf. 1 Sam 17:34&#8211;36). They anticipate Jacob&#8217;s reaction exactly (v33).</p>",
"21": "<p>Reuben&#8217;s intercession partially rehabilitates his character after the Bilhah incident (35:22) that cost him the firstborn blessing (49:3&#8211;4). His strategy is to deflect from murder rather than to confront it directly&#8212;he proposes the cistern as an alternative, intending to return and rescue Joseph. ANE social dynamics: Reuben as firstborn bore the greatest responsibility for family integrity; his intercession is also a firstborn&#8217;s attempt to exercise paternal-surrogate authority over his brothers.</p>",
"22": "<p>&#8220;Don&#8217;t shed any blood&#8221;&#8212;Reuben&#8217;s language invokes the blood-guilt prohibition (Gen 9:6; Num 35:33). Bloodshed on the land pollutes it; innocent blood cries from the ground (4:10). Reuben frames the cistern option as less culpable: they are not directly killing Joseph, merely exposing him. Whether he intends to return and rescue Joseph (the narrative&#8217;s explanation) or simply to avoid direct blood-guilt is left ambiguous. The narrative economy is typical of Genesis&#8212;motivations are shown through action, not interiority.</p>",
"23": "<p>The brothers strip Joseph of his robe first&#8212;the <em>kĕtōnet passîm</em>&#8212;before throwing him in. This detail is significant: the robe is the symbol of Jacob&#8217;s preferential love. Stripping it is the first act of vengeance, symbolically undoing Jacob&#8217;s favoritism before physically disposing of Joseph. They then use the robe in their deception (v31), making the instrument of Jacob&#8217;s love the instrument of his grief.</p>",
"24": "<p>&#8220;The cistern was empty; there was no water in it.&#8221; The redundancy is emphasis: Joseph will not drown. He is alive and will remain alive&#8212;the narrative is careful to establish this so the audience knows the cistern is a holding cell, not a tomb. The empty cistern will appear again as a potent image in Zechariah 9:11 (&#8220;prisoners of hope&#8221; released from &#8220;the waterless pit&#8221;), language the prophetic tradition applies to restoration from exile.</p>",
"25": "<p>The caravan of Ishmaelites from Gilead carries spices (<em>nĕḵōʾt</em>), balm (<em>ṣĕrî</em>), and myrrh (<em>lōṭ</em>)&#8212;luxury trade goods from the Gilead/Transjordan highlands destined for Egypt. This matches the known archaeology of the spice trade: aromatic resins from the Levant and Arabia were in high demand in Egypt for embalming, temple rites, and medicine. The caravan route via Dothan Valley was part of the international Via Maris connecting Syria/Mesopotamia to Egypt&#8212;a busy commercial artery, not a desert track.</p>",
"26": "<p>Judah&#8217;s intervention is motivated by pragmatism: &#8220;What will we gain if we kill our brother?&#8221; He frames it as a profit question, not an ethical one. Yet the result&#8212;preserving Joseph&#8217;s life&#8212;aligns with the divine purpose. Judah is not presented as noble here; he is calculating. The same calculating character drives his later story (ch 38), but in ch 44 Judah offers himself as a substitute for Benjamin&#8212;a trajectory from exploiter to self-sacrificing protector.</p>",
"27": "<p>&#8220;He is our brother, our own flesh and blood&#8221; (Heb. <em>kî ʾāḥînû bĕśārênû hûʾ</em>). The blood-kinship argument is invoked to justify selling rather than killing&#8212;a perverse half-mercy. The Ishmaelites are specifically chosen as buyers: they are Abraham&#8217;s descendants through Hagar/Ishmael, thus Joseph&#8217;s distant kin (cousins through Abraham). Selling him to kin rather than total strangers may have rationalized the act&#8212;or the narrative highlights the irony of kin trafficking kin.</p>",
"28": "<p>Twenty shekels of silver was the standard Middle Bronze Age slave price for a young male (attested in Old Babylonian texts, c. 1800&#8211;1600 BCE). By the Late Bronze Age the price rose to 30 shekels (Exod 21:32: the compensation for a slave gored by an ox). The precise price anchors the Joseph story in historical memory of ANE trade prices. The buyers are called &#8220;Midianite merchants&#8221; here but &#8220;Ishmaelites&#8221; in vv25, 27&#8212;reflecting either two sources or the ancient practice of using both ethnonyms for the same Arabian trading people (Midian = Abraham/Keturah&#8217;s son, 25:2; both groups occupied overlapping territories).</p>",
"29": "<p>Reuben&#8217;s return to the cistern and his horror&#8212;&#8220;he tore his clothes&#8221;&#8212;shows he was not present when the sale occurred, explaining how the other brothers transacted without his protest. Tearing clothes (<em>qāraʿ bĕgāḏāyw</em>) is the standard ANE and Israelite gesture of grief and self-abasement (cf. Job 1:20; 2 Sam 1:11); it publicly declares mourning and sometimes guilt. Reuben&#8217;s grief is genuine&#8212;his plan to rescue Joseph has failed not through opposition but through his absence.</p>",
"30": "<p>&#8220;Where can I turn now?&#8221; (Heb. <em>waʾănî ʾānāh ʾănî bāʾ</em>&#8212;lit. &#8220;and I, where shall I go?&#8221;). As firstborn, Reuben was responsible for Joseph&#8217;s safety; the loss of Joseph is catastrophic for him personally. The question is existential: he faces his father without the brother he was charged to protect. His paralysis here contrasts with Judah&#8217;s later willingness to act (44:33&#8211;34)&#8212;Reuben is the firstborn who cannot lead when it counts, confirming why the blessing passed to Judah.</p>",
"31": "<p>The goat-and-robe deception inverts ch 27: Jacob deceived Isaac using goatskin and his brother&#8217;s robe to steal Esau&#8217;s blessing. Now Jacob&#8217;s sons deceive their father using goat blood and Joseph&#8217;s robe to steal Joseph&#8217;s future. The poetic justice is exact: the deceiver is deceived by his own children using the same two elements&#8212;goat and garment. ANE audiences who recognized the parallel would see divine retribution operating through human action.</p>",
"32": "<p>The brothers present the robe and say &#8220;We found this. Examine it&#8230;&#8221; (<em>hakkēr-nāʾ</em>)&#8212;the same phrase Judah will use in 38:25 when Tamar presents his seal and staff, demanding he recognize (<em>hikkîr</em>) them. The verb <em>nākar</em> (recognize/identify) links the two deceptions. In ch 38 Judah&#8217;s own deception is turned back on him by the same demand for recognition&#8212;a narrative structure that shows justice operating through the same verbal and visual tokens.</p>",
"33": "<p>Jacob&#8217;s recognition is immediate: &#8220;It is my son&#8217;s robe!&#8221; The robe he had specially made to signal Joseph&#8217;s status now becomes the evidence of his death. His interpretation&#8212;&#8220;a ferocious animal has devoured him&#8221;&#8212;is exactly the cover story the brothers planned (v20). In ANE narrative convention, when a plan succeeds exactly as plotted, it signals either divine permission or an ironic futility to come (the &#8220;plans of humans vs. divine purposes&#8221; theme that runs through Proverbs 16:9; 19:21).</p>",
"34": "<p>Jacob&#8217;s mourning observances&#8212;tearing clothes, putting on sackcloth (<em>śaq</em>), mourning for &#8220;many days&#8221;&#8212;are standard ANE mourning rituals. Sackcloth was coarse goat or camel hair worn against the skin as an expression of grief and penitence; it was universally understood across the Levant and Mesopotamia. &#8220;Many days&#8221; suggests an extended mourning that violates the normal funeral period (7 days in Israelite custom; cf. 50:10), indicating that without a body to bury, Jacob cannot complete the mourning rite.</p>",
"35": "<p>&#8220;I will continue to mourn until I join my son in the grave&#8221;&#8212;the Hebrew <em>šĕʾôl</em> (grave/underworld) is the realm of the dead, shared by all. Jacob&#8217;s refusal of comfort is not merely emotional&#8212;it is the refusal of the social consolation ritual that marked reintegration after death. His daughters coming to comfort him (Heb. <em>bĕnōtāyw</em>, &#8220;daughters&#8221;&#8212;which daughters are unspecified, since only Dinah is named) shows the whole family unit attempting to restore normalcy while Jacob resists. The narrative preserves his grief as legitimate testimony to a loss whose real dimensions neither he nor the audience yet knows.</p>",
"36": "<p>&#8220;Meanwhile, the Midianites sold Joseph in Egypt to Potiphar, one of Pharaoh&#8217;s officials, the captain of the guard.&#8221; The narrative pivot is abrupt and devastating in its economy. Potiphar&#8217;s title (<em>śar haṭṭabbāḥîm</em>&#8212;&#8220;chief of the executioners/slaughterers,&#8221; often translated &#8220;captain of the guard&#8221;) places Joseph inside Pharaoh&#8217;s security apparatus from the start&#8212;a position of both danger and proximity to power. The name Potiphar is Egyptian (<em>P-di-p-Rʿ</em>, &#8220;he whom Ra has given&#8221;), the first Egyptian name in Genesis, signaling the full shift of narrative setting. Joseph enters Egypt not as a guest or diplomat but as chattel&#8212;and the audience knows from the dreams that this is not where the story ends.</p>"
}
}

